questionRound.0.question.9.answer: A strategy I used while playing this game was attempting to predict what the person with the other color in my square would choose. For example  if my payoff was red and my square had boxes consisting of numbers determined by X and Y for red and blue  I would go to the payoff square for blue to determine which combination he would choose. This would lead me back to other boxes to determine his behavior and so forth. This was just a strategy I adopted as the games progressed and it has worked for getting me the higher numbers for the most part because I have a better idea on which box to choose. Eventually you could even predict all the possible combinations  assuming that the other members of your team will be choosing the highest numbers because they want to earn the most number of tokens. This strategy fails to work if others do not choose the highest numbers and pick randomly. However  the incentive prevents us from doing so.

I was going through all the players strategies  in case i find a case where one player was better off definitely by choosing one option i followed back to mine and based on that choose my best option. When there was no definit advantage in choosing one for any player i made a decision starting from mine back through all the players until i got back to me and if i still choose the same that i stayed there if not than i just based on my decisions on the two people who had their decisions based on each other and finally mine was based on theirs. A lot of times though people choose definitely the wrong answers in the cases when one player had absolute advantage in choosing one but they still didnt take that into account that he was definitely going to choose that one and many times that ruined my strategy  because i expected everyone to play to their absolute best chance to win the most.

I looked for the square that had the two hightest numbers within one of the options and predicted that they would choose that option. Then I used that choice to determine what the person whose choice was dependant on that first participant would choose. I did this as many times as needed until I reached my own square. Knowing what I thought the person I was dependent on would likely choose I acted accordingly and chose the number that would grant me the hightst score with what my dependent would choose.

At first  there was a way where all participants could receive the maximum tokens for their color - it was just a matter of finding the choices. Later on  you could see the there was always one color where the top two choices were within the same row. This narrows down everyone else's choices dramatically  since one color is guaranteed to pick a particular row. For example  in Display 3  Orange's top two choices are both in Xo. Therefore  it's almost certain that Orange will pick Xo  therefore meaning that the number of different rewards Blue could receive is cut in half. Blue will most likely choose Yb because he no longer has access to the Yo category (and as such cannot earn 42 tokens - he'll take the next best thing). Accordingly  Green will choose Xg because that's how he'll make the most out of his available alternatives  and I (player Red) will choose Yr because that's how I can maximize my earnings out of the given alternatives. My strategy hinged on the one player who's two best choices were both in the same row - everyone else's choices are easy to figure out after that.

I would look at the other boxes to see who has the best payoff in both sqaures then using that go though each color to see who would play what based off of the color with the best payoff and made my choice according to that.
find the color that  no matter what any other choose  doesn't alter it's decision. Then keep tracking.

questionRound.0.question.9.answer: Unless my payoffs were both larger with one option no matter what the other color chose  I would first backtrack to the color who faced me on the other side of the matrix. I would go to their payoff matrix and analyze their possible choice based off of what color faced them in their matrix. I would keep backtracking until I felt generally confident that a certain color would choose a certain choice (i.e. if the color had a higher payoff with the X option no matter what compared to the Y option)  then go forward from there and base everyone else's choice off of that choice. Then I would base my choice off of what I thought every other color involved's choices were and hope that they weren't morons. Sorry if that doesn't make sense.

There is always one color that choose x (or y) is better than the other option no matter what other will choose. So basingon that comfired action  I can assume what other will choose until to my color.
I looked at the chances I had between the 2 boxes for each X or Y options as well as maybe estimated what the other color affecting my payoff might choose.
I went with the option that allowed for 2 better possible outcomes than the other option

There was always one board out of 4 that determines the whole outcome. One of the boards had an obvious choice (by obvious I mean that both options for xg were greater than both options for yg). Obviously in this case  green should select xg. Then I looked at who was the player affected by greens choice and I determined what I thought was their choice. I followed this process all the way down until I was reached. Sometimes  I was in the position when I had an obvious choice  but most of the time  I had to decipher what the other people would pick
I picked either x or y depending on which set had more big numbers.
